AGI - At 69 years old, the German conservative Friedrich Merz has long been derided calling it "a man of the past". Now, in the process of becoming a chancellor, after the victory of his Conservative side in the German legislative elections, he intends to embody the future and give confidence to a country in great doubt.
&nbsp;
It was a long way for this former rival of Angela Merkel, who had set him aside in the Democratic Christian Party (Cdu) in the early 2000s. The Conservative Union, which also belongs to the small Bavarian party Csu, was a winner in the early general elections with almost 29%, in front of the extreme right of AFD and the Social-Democrats. For the Cdu in fact it is not a triumph, indeed it is the second worst result in the history of the movement, after the historical minimum of 2021, pairs to 24,2%. But his victory remains intact.
&nbsp;
"We will get to work tomorrow morning!", he said after the announcement of the results, promising to commit to "to quickly form a government capable of acting", because "the world cannot wait". Impulsively and without government experience, he promised to "restore pride" to the main European economy, weakened by a deep crisis of his industrial and geopolitical model. Amateur driver and owner of a private jet, Merz preaches a trend reversal with respect to the generous migration policy inherited by Angela Merkel (2005-2021). According to him, only a restrictive policy in this area can effectively curb the rise of AfD.
&nbsp;
At the end of January, in Germany, he broke a post-war tabooo, which had seen the traditional parties forbid any cooperation with the extreme right, having approved a resolution on the right of asylum with the votes of this party. Accused of having initiated a normalization of the anti-migrant party, it immediately excluded - despite the exhortations in this sense of the Trump administration - any alliance of government with the AfD, founded in 2013 by former Cdu executives.
&nbsp;
The German left, however, has doubts. Since he took over the Conservative Party leadership in January 2022 after two failed attempts, Merz traced a demarcation line with Angela Merkel's centrist inheritance, moving the rudder to the right. A revenge against the woman who in 2002 had removed him from the strategic position of president of the Cdu parliamentary group, prompting him in 2009 to redevelop in the financial sector, in particular at BlackRock, one of the greatest asset managers in the world.
&nbsp;
Yesterday he promised to bring Germany back to the centre of the European game with "a strong voice" to defend the interests of the continent, even if necessary, against the United States of Donald Trump. Despite this, "many in the Cdu believe that Merz and Trump might get along. Merz knows the United States, has had a career in the private sector, so he is also a businessman, which should please the "deal maker" of the White House," says Der Spiegel.
&nbsp;
With a "anti-woke" sensibility, this Catholic married to a lawyer and father of three children also expressed himself against equality between women and men in a government under his guidance. At international level, he remains a convinced supporter of military aid to Ukraine against the Russian invasion, while Donald Trump is turning his back.
&nbsp;
"Now it is important that Europeans agree very quickly on a common strategy to tackle this problem," he said. In this context, Friedrich Merz looks both at Poland and France to advance the EU, convinced that the balance of power in Europe has moved towards the East.
&nbsp;
This could mark a change over its predecessors to the stationary. On the economic front, this convinced liberal wants to reduce taxes on society and bureaucracy, as well as to tighten the conditions of social assistance. "Work must return to be a pleasure," he tirelessly argues, excluding any increase in the minimum wage.
&nbsp;
Impopolar and often considered haughty, during the election campaign tried to project the image of an accessible and human elected official, showing himself with a glass of beer in his hand during a meeting or sitting at a table in front of a burger in a post on Instagram. In the course of a television debate he also revealed little known private tragedies: the death of the younger sister in a road accident, at the age of 21, and then of the brother suffering from multiple sclerosis. Events that "have left deep marks" in his family, he confessed.
